# Documentations
As people answered before me, the standard behavior of Python defined in the [documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/reference/expressions.html#binary-arithmetic-operations):

&gt; In the latter case, sequence repetition is performed; a negative repetition factor yields an empty sequence.

---

# Source Code

If you wonder why it happens, you can follow CPython&#39;s source code:

Start with the code in [abstract.c](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/e42b705188271da108de42b55d9344642170aa2b/Objects/abstract.c):

```
PyObject *
PyNumber_Multiply(PyObject *v, PyObject *w)
{
    PyObject *result = binary_op1(v, w, NB_SLOT(nb_multiply));
    ...
        if  (mv &amp;&amp; mv-&gt;sq_repeat) {
            return sequence_repeat(mv-&gt;sq_repeat, v, w);
        }
        else if (mw &amp;&amp; mw-&gt;sq_repeat) {
            return sequence_repeat(mw-&gt;sq_repeat, w, v);
        }
    ...
}
```

Then, on [listobject.c](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/3c87a667bb367ace1de6bd1577fdb4f66947da52/Objects/listobject.c):
```c
static PySequenceMethods list_as_sequence = {
    ...
    (ssizeargfunc)list_repeat,                  /* sq_repeat */
    ...
}
```

Jump to [list_repeat](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/3c87a667bb367ace1de6bd1577fdb4f66947da52/Objects/listobject.c#L558):

```c
static PyObject *
list_repeat(PyListObject *a, Py_ssize_t n)
{
    ...
    if (n &lt; 0)
        n = 0;
    ...
    if (size == 0)
        return PyList_New(0);
    ...
}
```

